properties.name: Advice
properties.webBody:
This is a Final Minor Flood Warning for the Ovens River at Wangaratta. 

MINOR FLOODING TO EASE SLOWLY ALONG THE OVENS RIVER AT WANGARATTA DURING MONDAY

MINOR FLOODING EASED ALONG THE KING RIVER AT DOCKER RD BRIDGE

No significant rainfall has been recorded since 9:00 am Sunday. Rainfall totals of 10-20 mm are forecast for Tuesday into Wednesday, with isolated higher totals over the ranges. It may cause small renewed river level rises, but they are expected to remain below minor flood levels.

Minor flooding is expected to ease at Wangaratta late Monday morning. River levels eased just below the minor flood level at Docker Rd Bridge, however, they will remain elevated for the next few days.

Ovens River downstream of Rocky Point:
Minor flooding is easing slowly along the Ovens River at Wangaratta.

The Ovens River at Wangaratta is currently at 11.99 metres and easing slowly, with minor flooding. The Ovens River at Wangaratta is expected to fall below the minor flood level (11.90 m) Monday afternoon.

The threat of flooding is reduced. Stay informed - monitor your local conditions and beware of hazards remaining in the warning area.
What you should do:

  • Be prepared to act if your situation changes.
  • Floodwater is dangerous - never enter floodwater.
  • Drive slowly, obey all roadblocks and never drive through floodwaters.

If your home or business has been flooded:
  • Check for building damage before you enter.
  • Have all electrical and gas equipment professionally tested before use.
  • Clean and dry out the building as soon as possible.

Call Triple Zero (000) in a life threatening emergency. For emergency assistance from the SES call 132 500.
Impacts in your area: 
  • Damage to roads and buildings caused by flooding may still exist in your area. 
  • Caravan parks and camping grounds may be flooded.
  • Waking tracks will still be flood affected around the Ovens and King Rivers
This message was issued by State Emergency Service.

This will be the last warning for this flood. 

Use multiple sources to stay informed:
  • www.emergency.vic.gov.au
  • VicEmergency Hotline - freecall 1800 226 226
  • VicEmergency app
  • Facebook or Twitter (#vicfloods)
  • Tune in to ABC Local Radio, commercial and designated community radio stations, or Sky News TV.

Accessibility:
The following services can help you, or someone you know, access information during an emergency.
  • To access this information in other languages call the Translating and Interpreting Service on 131 450 (freecall) and ask them to call VicEmergency Hotline.
  • If you are deaf, hard of hearing, or have a speech/communication impairment contact National Relay Service on 1800 555 677 and ask them to call the VicEmergency Hotline.

properties.webBody:
This Minor Flood Warning is being issued for the Kiewa River downstream of Mongans Bridge.

MINOR FLOODING TO CONTINUE ALONG THE KIEWA RIVER AT BANDIANA 

MINOR FLOODING EASED ALONG THE KIEWA RIVER AT KIEWA (MAIN STREAM)

No significant rainfall has been recorded since 9:00 am Sunday. Rainfall totals of 10 - 20 mm are forecast for Tuesday into Wednesday, with isolated higher totals over the ranges. This may cause small renewed river level rises.

Kiewa River downstream of Mongans Bridge:
Minor flooding is continuing along the Kiewa River downstream of Mongans Bridge.

The Kiewa River at Kiewa (Main Stream) is currently at 3.20 metres and easing slowly, below the minor flood level. Small renewed rises are possible with forecast rainfall, but the Kiewa River at Kiewa (Main Stream) is expected to remain below the minor flood level (3.30 m).

The Kiewa River at Bandiana is currently at 2.90 metres and steady, with minor flooding. The Kiewa River at Bandiana is likely to remain above the minor flood level (2.80 m) over the next few days.

Stay informed - monitor your local conditions and remain alert.
What you should do: 

  • Be prepared to act if your situation changes.
  • You should stay informed by listening to emergency broadcasters and monitoring warnings.
  • Farmers should consider moving livestock and machinery to higher ground.
  • Floodwater is toxic - never play or swim in floodwater.
  • Floodwater is dangerous - never drive, walk or ride through floodwater.
Impacts in your area: 

  • High river levels and potential flooding in areas close to rivers and streams.
  • Caravan parks and camping grounds may be flooded.
  • Local roads may be closed and low bridges may be underwater.
This message was issued by State Emergency Service.

The next update is expected by 13/06/2023 12:00 pm or as the situation changes.

Use multiple sources to stay informed:
  • www.emergency.vic.gov.au
  • VicEmergency Hotline - freecall 1800 226 226
  • VicEmergency app
  • Facebook or Twitter (#vicfloods)
  • Tune in to ABC Local Radio, commercial and designated community radio stations, or Sky News TV.

Accessibility: 
The following services can help you, or someone you know, access information during an emergency. 
  • To access this information in other languages call the Translating and Interpreting Service on 131 450 (freecall) and ask them to call VicEmergency Hotline. 
  • If you are deaf, hard of hearing, or have a speech/communication impairment contact National Relay Service on 1800 555 677 and ask them to call the VicEmergency Hotline.
